[[Image:George Lansbury - cartoon - Project Gutenberg eText 17653.png|thumb|200px|''Under a cloud (with a silver lining)'' (1920). A [[cartoon]] depicting [[George Lansbury]]. Captions: Under a cloud (with a golden lining) Comrade Lansbury. "Thanks to my faithful brolski not a drop has touched me." [''Loud crows from "Daily Herald" bird.''] Possibly reflecting an allegation of [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] funding for the Independent Labour Party. Lansbury founded the Daily Herald.<ref>Cartoon from [[Punch (magazine)|Punch]], [http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/17653 Punch, or the London Charivari, Volume 159, September 22, 1920 by Various]</ref>]]
A '''silver lining''' is a [[metaphor]] for [[optimism]] in the common English-language which means a negative occurrence may have a positive aspect to it.<ref>{{cite book|title=every cloud has a silver lining idiom definition|url=http://www.theidioms.com/every-cloud-has-a-silver-lining/}}</ref>
== Origin == The origin of the phrase is most likely traced to [[John Milton]]'s "[[Comus (John Milton)|Comus]]" (1634) with the lines, {{quote|<poem>Was I deceiv'd, or did a sable cloud Turn forth her silver lining on the night?<ref>[http://www.phrases.org.uk/bulletin_board/18/messages/407.html Re: Every cloud has a silver lining]</ref></poem>}}
